1.d4 {The Queen pawn opening is equally popular like 1.e4}

1...d5 {Identical response from Black}

2.c4 {The Queen's Gambit}

2...e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined or QGD is on the board}

3.Nc3 {Developing a piece and putting more pressure on the d5 pawn.}

3...Nf6 {Black protects the d5 pawn further}

4.cxd5 {The exchange variation}

4...exd5 {4...Nxd5 is also a playable option that does not allow the annoying pin on g5}

5.Bg5 {The positional variation or the Carlsbad variation where the Knight is pinned and pressure applied on the d5 pawn}

5...c6 {A solid response protecting the pawn on d5.}

6.Qc2 {The Reshevsky variation where the main idea is to make life of the Bishop on c8 difficult. This move robs the f5 square}

6...h6 {Putting the question to the Bishop}

7.Bh4 {Better to keep the pin rather than retreating with Bd2 or Bf4}

7...Bd6 {Black wants to castle soon}

8.e3 {Prepares Bd3 and Kingside development}

8...O-O 9.Bd3 {White develops the Bishop and adds more steel to the b1-h7 diagonal}
9...Re8 {The Rook is developed on the semi-open file considering the fact that White's King is still on the e1 square}

10.Nge2 {White's Knight does not come to the natural f3 square as this allows Black to play ...Bg4. White's main idea here 
is to restrict the development of the Bishop on c8 as much as he can.}

10...Na6 {Black wants to play ...Nb4 and eliminates White's light-squared Bishop.But I feel that this is a hasty move. 10...b6 followed by ...Bb7 or ...Nbd7 was better}

11.Bxa6 bxa6 {White damages the pawn structure and is looking to exploit the doubled a-pawns and the backward c6 pawn in the long run}

12.Bg3 {White asks Black to trade off the dark-squared Bishops. Black would be better off not to do this as in the long run White's pair of Knights would be much better than Black's 
moribund light-squared Bishop and the Knight on f6}

12...Bxg3 {Is this a mistake to exchange the active Bishop for the inactive one? Only time will tell.}

13.Nxg3 {13.hxg3 is the top engine recommendation.
But having an open h-file  after self-inflicted doubled g2 and g3 pawns is beyond comprehension}

13...h5 {Black's idea is to play ...h4 and kick away the Knight. Then Black will play ...h3 and create a "thorn" pawn. 
In this case White will have to push g3 to keep the g-file closed. But this allows the Black pawn on h3 
unhindered stay creating long-term problems for White. This thorn pawn formation is a favourite of chess engines like Stockfish and neural network 
behemoth like Alphazero}
 
14.h3 {White does not want Black to play ...h3 at any cost and hence occupies the h3 square himself. 14.O-O would be a mistake as Black can then create the thorn pawn as follows: 14...h4 15.Ne2 h3 16.g3 with an unclear position}

14...h4 {Black gains more space on the h-file and attacks the Knight}

15.Nge2 {15.Nf1 Qd6! is a resourceful move that threatens ...Qxd4 and Black has sufficient counterplay}

15...Nh5 {Vacating the g5 square for the Queen as Black wants to launch a Kingside counter-offensive. After ...Qg5, ...Bf5 becomes a possibility} 

16.O-O* {White takes the King to safety}

