8...Bxc3 9.bxc3 {White eliminates Black's Bishop pair}

9...Qc7 {The most common continuation Black does not commit to any pawn breaks in the centre}

10.Bb2 {White places the Bishop on the a1-h8 diagonal and wants to play cxd5 followed by c4 to activate the dark-squared Bishop}

10...dxc4 {Black could also have played 10...Na5 forcing White to play 11.cxd5}

11.Bxc4 {White now has the Bishop pair but Black is not too bad either}

11...e5 {Putting more pressure on the d4 pawn and clearing the c8-g4 diagonal for the light-squared Bishop on c8}

12.h3 {...Bg4 is an annoying pin that White prevents}

12...Bf5 {Black develops the last remaining Bishop and connects Rooks}

